      title: "The Particular Frequency of Jodelle Vasquez",
      synopsis: "",
      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
    <p class="mb-6">She integrated the way water integrates — not by force, not by announcement, but by finding the level. Within two weeks she was simply there, at the table, at their after-school configurations, in the group chat she had been added to without fanfare. The chat had been called The Problem for three years. She did not suggest renaming it. She added a black moon emoji to the group name and nobody removed it.<br>They learned her in pieces, the way you learn anyone who doesn't offer themselves in a single complete presentation.<br>She read — voraciously, eclectically, the way Marcus read but wider and stranger. He read literature; she read everything, in the order that interested her, which was no discernible order. Philosophy beside crime novels beside field guides to North American fungi beside a Victorian ghost anthology beside a graphic novel about the French Revolution. Her reading was not curated for impression. It just was.<br>She drew. Not in art class particularly — she drew in margins, on the backs of receipts, on the condensation of windows in winter. Small, detailed drawings — architectural in their precision — of things she was looking at, or things she was seeing that weren't there. It took them a while to figure out the second category existed.<br>She was funny in a way that was easy to miss because she delivered everything at the same low, even pitch — the absurdist observations, the genuine statements, the occasional thing that was so true it almost hurt — all in the same tone, unhurried, like a radio station playing through a wall. You had to be listening. Priya was always listening. Marcus was listening but wouldn't admit how carefully. Danny caught about sixty percent of it and laughed every time, reliably, which Jodelle seemed to find genuinely endearing.<br>"She's different," Marcus said once, to Theo, after school.<br>"Yes," Theo said.<br>"Not bad different."<br>"No."<br>"Just — " He couldn't find it.<br>"Tuned to a different frequency," Theo said.<br>Marcus pointed at him. "That."</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    <p class="mb-6">The switching — as they came to call it, later, in their own heads, none of them ever putting the word to each other — was something you noticed only after you'd known her long enough to have a baseline.<br>She would be completely present — sharp, dry, funny, tracking every conversational thread simultaneously with the ease of someone who had done it her whole life in rooms full of strangers — and then, without transition, without drama, she would be gone. Not physically. She'd still be sitting there. But her focus would shift to somewhere slightly off the edges of the visible, and she'd hold that position for ten seconds or thirty seconds or three minutes, and then come back, smooth as a tide, as though no time had passed.<br>It wasn't daydreaming. Daydreaming has a quality of absence — the person isn't there. With Jodelle, it was more like she was more there than usual. More focused. Just on something nobody else could see.<br>"Jo." Marcus would say it with a snap.<br>"I'm here," she'd say, without turning immediately.<br>"Where were you?"<br>A pause. "Listening."<br>"To what?"<br>She'd look at him then. "Just — the room." And she'd go back to whatever they'd been doing, and it would have been easy to dismiss as artistic temperament or introvert recharge if it weren't for the fact that she sometimes, afterwards, would say something that suggested she'd heard and processed everything that had happened while she was away.<br>The other thing — the thing that nobody named because naming it would have made it a thing — was the people.<br>Not often. But occasionally Jodelle would reference someone in a conversation — casually, parenthetically, the way you reference a mutual acquaintance — and the someone would be a person none of them had ever seen her talk to, sometimes a person none of them could place at all.<br>"The guy who tends the garden behind the old municipal building told me the soil there used to be a different color," she said once, walking past it. "Before they changed the drainage."<br>"What guy?" Priya said.<br>Jodelle glanced at the garden. Empty. "He's not there now."<br>"Has he ever been there when we've been there?"<br>A small pause. "I think so."<br>She kept walking. The moment closed. Nobody made it a thing, because with Jodelle these moments landed gently and passed gently and she was always so calm about them that alarm felt disproportionate.<br>This was perhaps the truest thing about Jodelle Vasquez: she made the inexplicable feel like weather. Present, noted, unremarkable.</p>
</div>`
